After looking at the data provided for this question - this last week's average is $3.87 and it is unlikely to drop or rise by more than 17 cents in a week. This has only happened twice in the last 28 years. Both times did occur in November timeframe, but the price was rapidly dropping in the weeks leading up and past Thanksgiving. Although the prices has dropped in the last few weeks, it is only dropping a couple of cents each week - not a large drop.

The national average continues to decrease. There are several examples of a decrease by more than 6 cents in a week, but most decreases are below 5 cents per week, keeping this in the $3.70-$4.05 block.

Gasoline prices have been dropping considerably as global oil prices come down, releases from the US SRP continue, and demand continues to drag (slowing economy, China's COVID lockdowns, etc.). However, OPEC is meeting this week and will be discussing options to reduce global output by 500k, 1m, or 1.5m bpd. At the same time, US SPR releases are slowing over the next month (though not stopping). I think OPEC will take action to try and stabilize oil prices, and one benchmark is US consumer gasoline prices. Thus I think it will stabilize or slightly increase in the next roughly 1.5 months.

Looking back at data since 2001, prices went down 12x in Oct in 21 years and 16x times in 21 years in Nov (16/21 ~75% it will go down in Nov). Looking at years where prices went down both in Oct and Nov - it decreased an average of ~$0.22 cents from Sept to Nov (01,03,05,08,11-15, &20). So starting at a base rate, I think it will decrease by ~$0.22 cents from Sep price. I started out with monthly trends because it was easier to aggregate. Using $3.82 as the avg in Sept 2022 and subtracting $0.22 equals $3.60 as the base rate. Source: https://www.eia.gov/dnav/pet/hist/LeafHandler.ashx?n=pet&s=emm_epm0_pte_nus_dpg&f=m

The average price of gasoline in the US as of the week of 9/26/22 was $3.832 per gallon. The price had been falling since peaking at $5.107 per gallon in mid June, but the figure has risen in the last week; the price was $3.771 for the week of 9/19. This recent increase leads me to believe that prices may not continue to decline as sharply as they have been doing since June.
